When you exceed your query limit the API rejects requests with a 429 (Too Many Requests) error and returns rate-limit details. Typical responses include:

- A 429 JSON response saying the monthly query limit was exceeded, e.g.
  {
    "success": false,
    "error": "Monthly query limit exceeded",
    "usage": { "current": 101, "max": 100, "exceeded": true, "reset_at": "2026-02-01T00:00:00Z" }
  }
- For per-minute limits you may get a RATE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED error telling you to retry after N seconds.
- Responses also include rate-limit headers (X-RateLimit-Limit, X-RateLimit-Remaining, X-RateLimit-Reset) so you can see when the limit resets.

In some billing/credits cases an INSFFICIENT_CREDITS error may be returned when you lack the needed credits.

When a user exceeds their query limit the API returns an HTTP 429 (Too Many Requests) error and includes rate/usage details. For monthly query limits you’ll get a response like:

{
  "success": false,
  "error": "Monthly query limit exceeded",
  "usage": {
    "current": 101,
    "max": 100,
    "exceeded": true,
    "reset_at": "2026-02-01T00:00:00Z"
  }
}

Responses also include rate-limit headers (X-RateLimit-Limit, X-RateLimit-Remaining, X-RateLimit-Reset). In some contexts you may see related error payloads/codes such as RATE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED or INSUFFICIENT_CREDITS indicating the same condition.
